node.text:
A cougar stalked a man for over 6 minutes - during his run through Slate Canyon near Provo. 

Video by @kunkyle 

What to do when approached by a cougar?

The DWR states it’s important to know what to do if you ever come in contact with a cougar, especially if you’re an avid hiker or trail runner. They suggest that you: 

- Stop. Never run from a cougar and do not approach the cougar
- Maintain eye contact with the animal 
- Stand up tall
- Do not crouch or squat
- Make yourself look bigger by raising and waving your arms or jacket above your head
- Talk firmly in a loud voice, back away slowly, and leave the area
- Pick up children and pets or keep them very close
- Fight back if you are attacked!
- Protect your head and neck
- Wild Aware Utah also has information detailing how to protect yourself from a cougar. 

Warning for explicit language!

node.text:
Giraffe chase! 😂🦒
Video by @mattyardleyafrica ,
Here’s what he had to say about this unique moment:

“This young male giraffe was orphaned at a young age and hand reared until he was able to survive in his own and be released back into to wild. So although this may look like an angry charge, it’s just the giraffe “keeping up with the herd” that he imprinted on as a youngster. 

The giraffe chase happened unexpectedly and we did not force this moment. We do not encourage this type of interaction at all and in fact we avoid it at all costs so that the animal remains wild and free from human interaction. This was an unexpected and unavoidable moment.”

Thanks for sharing Matt! 
#naturegeography

That magical bioluminescent glow via @jordan_robins , an unforgettable and captivating sight you'll be lucky to witness at Jervis Bay in Australia. 🇦🇺

Notoriously difficult to capture in photographs and videos, bioluminescence can only be spotted at a few locations around the world. In Jervis Bay, the best time to catch sight of this natural wonder varies but is usually seen between the months of May and August. 💙

Is seeing this in real life part of your bucket list? Or are you one of the lucky few who have already seen this? 🤩

📸 @jordan_robins
📍 Jervis Bay, Australia 
#naturegeography

Italy is opening back up and one of the most unique and beautiful places you can visit is Alberobello. 

Video by @gabdetails 

This special little destination is famous for the distinctive type of dwelling called “trulli.” These small whitewashed buildings are circular in shape with grey pointy roofs that date back to 14th century. 

Pro tip: spend the night here. The trulli look magical in the evening when they are all lit up.
